{"title_page": "Van Province", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|Province of Turkey}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->| name                            = Van Province\n| native_name                     = Van ili<!-- if different from the English name -->\n| native_name_lang                = tr<!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"tr\" for Turkish. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type                 = [[Provinces of Turkey|Province of Turkey]]\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_caption                   = \n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = <!-- maps and coordinates ------>\n| image_map                       = Van in Turkey.svg\n| mapsize                         = 300px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Van Province in Turkey \n<!-- location ------------------>| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[Turkey]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[First-level NUTS of Turkey|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Central East Anatolia Region (statistical)|Central East Anatolia]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[Second-level NUTS of Turkey|Subregion]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Van Subregion|Van]]\n| seat_type                       = Provincial seat and largest city\n| seat                            = \n| seat1_type                      = Largest city\n| seat1                           = <!-- coordinates -->\n| coordinates                     = <!-- government type, leaders -->\n| leader_title                    = [[Electoral districts of Turkey|Electoral district]]\n| leader_name                     = [[Van (electoral district)|Van]]\n| leader_title1                   = Governor\n| leader_name1                    = Mehmet Emin Bilmez\n| total_type                      = Total\n| area_total_km2                  = 19,069\n| population_footnotes            = {{wikidata|reference|P1082|P585=2018}}\n| population_total                = {{wikidata|property|raw|P1082|P585=2018}}\n| population_as_of                = 2018\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_urban                = \n| population_urban_footnotes      = \n| population_rural                = \n| population_rural_footnotes      = \n| area_code_type                  = <!-- defaults to: Area code(s) -->\n| area_code                       = 0432<ref>[http://www.ttrehber.turktelekom.com.tr/trk-web/alankodlari.html Area codes page of Turkish Telecom website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822080457/http://www.ttrehber.turktelekom.com.tr/trk-web/alankodlari.html |date=2011-08-22 }} {{in lang|tr}}</ref>\n| registration_plate              = 65\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Van Province''' ({{lang-tr|Van ili}}, {{lang-hy|\u054e\u0561\u0576}}; {{lang-ku|Wan}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/lawmaker-proposes-changing-name-of-eastern-van-province-to-wan-57128|title=Lawmaker proposes changing name of eastern Van province to \u2018Wan\u2019 - Turkey News|website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref>; {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0627\u0646}}) is a [[Provinces of Turkey|province]] in eastern Turkey, between [[Lake Van]] and the [[Iran]]ian border. It is 19,069&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> in area and had a population of 1,035,418 at the end of 2010. Its adjacent provinces are [[Bitlis Province|Bitlis]] to the west, [[Siirt Province|Siirt]] to the southwest, [[\u015e\u0131rnak Province|\u015e\u0131rnak]] and [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Hakk\u00e2ri]] to the south, and [[A\u011fr\u0131 Province|A\u011fr\u0131]] to the north. The capital is the city of [[Van, Turkey|Van]]. The majority of the province's population is Kurdish,<ref>{{cite book|last=Watts|first=Nicole F.|title=Activists in Office: Kurdish Politics and Protest in Turkey (Studies in Modernity and National Identity)|date=2010|publisher=University of Washington Press|location=Seattle|isbn=978-0-295-99050-7|page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=yXWl40KJfKEC&pg=PA167&dq=Kars+(about+20+percent+Kurdish)&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DY5DU7jKJ4qc2QXYhYCACQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kars%20(about%2020%20percent%20Kurdish)&f=false 167]}}</ref> and has a sizable Azerbaijani minority ([[K\u00fcres\u00fcnni]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kuresunniler.com/245/kuresunnilerin-turkiyede-yasadiklari-yerler/|title=K\u00fcres\u00fcnnilerin T\u00fcrkiye'de Ya\u015fad\u0131klar\u0131 Yerler - K\u00fcres\u00fcnniler Tarih ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Platformu|date=2014-04-12|work=K\u00fcres\u00fcnniler Tarih ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Platformu|access-date=2018-04-08|language=tr-TR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kora-sonni|title=KORA-SONNI \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|last=electricpulp.com|website=www.iranicaonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref> The current [[W\u0101li#Turkish term|Governor]] is Mehmet Emin Bilmez.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.van.gov.tr/|title=T.C. Van Valili\u011fi Resmi Web Sitesi|website=www.van.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThis area was the heartland of [[Armenians]], who lived in these areas from the time of Hayk in the 3rd millennium BCE right up to the late 19th century when the Ottoman Empire seized all the land from the natives.<ref>{{Cite book\n  | editor-last = Hofmann\n  | editor-first = Tessa \n  | title = Verfolgung, Vertreibung und Vernichtung der Christen im Osmanischen Reich 1912-1922 |trans-title=Persecution, Expulsion and Annihilation of the Christian Population in the Ottoman Empire 1912-1922\n  | publisher = M\u00fcnster: LIT\n  | year=2004\n  | isbn = 3-8258-7823-6}}</ref> In the 9th century BC the Van area was the center of the [[Urartu|Urartian kingdom]].<ref>European History in a World Perspective - p. 68 by Shepard Bancroft Clough</ref> The area was a major Armenian population center. The region came under the control of the [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Orontid dynasty|Orontids]] in the 7th century BC and later [[Persian Empire|Persians]] in the mid-6th century BC. By the early 2nd century BC it was part of the [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Kingdom of Armenia]]. It became an important center during the reign of the [[Armenia]]n king, [[Tigranes II of Armenia|Tigranes II]], who founded the city of [[Tigranocerta|Tigranakert]] in the 1st century BC.<ref>The Journal of Roman Studies \u2013 p. 124 by Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies</ref> With the Seljuq victory at the [[Battle of Malazgirt]] in 1071, just north of [[Lake Van]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historymedren.about.com/od/aentries/a/11_alparslan.htm|title=Alp Arslan: Article from the 1911 Encyclopedia|author= Melissa Snell|publisher=About Education}}</ref> it became a part of the [[Seljuq Empire]] and later the [[Ottoman Empire]] during their century long wars with their neighboring Iranian [[Safavid]] arch rivals, in which Selim I managed to conquer the area over the latter. The area continued to be contested and was passed on between the Ottoman Empire and the Safavids (and their subsequent successors, the [[Afsharids]] and [[Qajar dynasty|Qajars]]) for many centuries afterwards, all the way up to during the 19th century when it became the [[Van Vilayet]].\n\n=== In Turkey ===\nIn 1927 the office of the [[Inspector general|Inspector General]] was created, which governed with martial law.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Jongerden|first=Joost|title=The Settlement Issue in Turkey and the Kurds: An Analysis of Spatical Policies, Modernity and War|date=2007-01-01|publisher=BRILL|year=2007|isbn=978-90-04-15557-2|location=|pages=53|language=en}}</ref> The province was included in the first [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate General]] (''Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015flik,'' UM) over which the Inspector General ruled. The UM span over the provinces of [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Hakk\u00e2ri]], [[Siirt Province|Siirt]], Van, [[Mardin Province|Mardin]], [[Bitlis Province|Bitlis]], [[\u015eanl\u0131urfa Province|Sanl\u0131urfa]], [[Elaz\u0131\u011f Province|Elazi\u011f]] and [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbak\u0131r]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bayir|first=Derya|title=Minorities and Nationalism in Turkish Law|date=2016-04-22|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-09579-8|location=|pages=139|language=en}}</ref> The Inspectorate General were dissolved in 1952 during the Government of the [[Democrat Party (Turkey, 1946\u201361)|Democrat Party]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fleet|first=Kate|title=The Cambridge History of Turkey|last2=Kunt|first2=I. Metin|last3=Kasaba|first3=Re\u015fat|last4=Faroqhi|first4=Suraiya|date=2008-04-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62096-3|location=|pages=343|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBetween July 1987 and July 2000 Van Province was within the [[OHAL]] region, which was ruled by a Governor within a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/pdfid/414d86ab4.pdf|title=Case of Dogan and others v. Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=21|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n==== Modern history ====\nAccording to the 2012 Metropolitan Municipalities Law (Law No. 6360), all Turkish provinces with a population more than 750 000, will have a [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|metropolitan municipality]] and the [[List of districts of Turkey|districts]] within the metropolitan municipalities will be second level municipalities. The law also creates new districts within the provinces in addition to present districts.<ref>[http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2012/12/20121206-1.htm Official gazette {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> These changes will be effective after the local elections in 2014.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nThus, in 2014, the city of [[Van, Turkey|Van]] became a Metropolitan Municipality.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Earthquakes ==\nIn Van province occurred several earthquakes. In 1881 an earthquake occurred and caused the death of 95 people.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1941, Van suffered a destructive [[1941 Van\u2013Erci\u015f earthquake|5.9 M<sub>w</sub> earthquake]]. Two more [[2011 Van earthquakes|earthquakes occurred in 2011]] in which 644 people died and 2608 people were injured.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nat-hazards-earth-syst-sci.net/12/3337/2012/nhess-12-3337-2012.pdf|title=Van earthquakes (23 October 2011 and 9 November 2011) and performance of masonry and adobe structures|last=G\u00fcney|first=D.|date=|website=Natural Hazards and Earth System Sciences|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> In a [[2011 Van earthquake|7.2 M<sub>w</sub> earthquake]] on 23 October 2011, more than 500 people were killed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2011/11/09/world/turkey-earthquake/index.html|title=At least 5 dead in quake in eastern Turkey|last=Staff|first=By the CNN Wire|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> On 9 November 2011, a 5.6 M<sub>w</sub> magnitude earthquake killed also several people and caused buildings to collapse.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Districts ==\nVan Province is divided into 13 districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yenisafak.com/yerel-secim-2019/van-ili-secim-sonuclari|title=Van Se\u00e7im Sonu\u00e7lar\u0131 \u2013 31 Mart 2019 Van Yerel Se\u00e7im sonu\u00e7lar\u0131|last=\u015eafak|first=Yeni|date=2019-11-14|website=Yeni \u015eafak|language=tr-TR|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Bah\u00e7esaray (District), Van|Bah\u00e7esaray]]\n* [[Ba\u015fkale]]\n* [[\u00c7ald\u0131ran (District), Van|\u00c7ald\u0131ran]]\n* [[\u00c7atak (District), Van|\u00c7atak]]\n* [[Edremit (District), Van|Edremit]]\n* [[Erci\u015f]]\n* [[Geva\u015f]]\n* [[G\u00fcrp\u0131nar (District), Van|G\u00fcrp\u0131nar]]\n* [[\u0130pekyolu]]\n* [[Muradiye (District), Van|Muradiye]]\n* [[\u00d6zalp (District), Van|\u00d6zalp]]\n* [[Saray (District), Van|Saray]]\n* [[Tu\u015fpa]]\n}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Urartian fort in \u00c7avu\u015ftepe.jpg|[[Haykaberd]] or \u00c7avu\u015ftepe\nFile:Hosap-castle (17).jpg|[[Ho\u015fap Castle]]\nFile:Muradiye Falls 2.JPG|[[Muradiye Fall]]\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Medieval Armenian monasteries in the Van Province\">\nImage:Akdamar and mountain.jpg|The [[Armenian Cathedral of the Holy Cross]] (10th century) on [[Akdamar Island]]\nImage:Narekavank.jpg|The Armenian ''[[Narekavank|Monastery of Narek]]'' (10th century)\nImage:Varagavank.jpg|[[Varagavank]] Armenian monastery (11th century)\nImage:Saint Bartholomew Monastery.jpg|The Armenian '' [[Saint Bartholomew Monastery|Monastery of Saint Bartholomew]]'' (13th century)\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Islamic monuments in the Van Province\">\nFile:OTAltVanOsmanMoschee.jpg|Ruined Ottoman mosque in the old ruined part of Van city (16th century)\nFile:Geva\u015f T\u00fcrbe 01.JPG|Tomb of Halime Hatun in [[Geva\u015f]] (14th century)\nFile:OTAltVanOsmanMinarett.jpg|Ruined Ottoman minaret in the old part of Van city\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Van Province}}\n* [[Ottoman Armenian Population]]\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)]]\n* [[2011 Van earthquake]]\n* [[Yazidis]]\n* [[2020 Van avalanches]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/van Pictures of the capital of this province]\n\n{{coord|38|29|57|N|43|40|13|E|region:TR-65_type:adm1st|display=title}}\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Van}}\n{{Provinces of Turkey}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Van Province| ]]\n[[Category:Armenian Highlands]]\n[[Category:Turkish Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Short description|Province of Turkey}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->| name     