s.google.com/books?id=yXWl40KJfKEC&pg=PA167&dq=Kars+(about+20+percent+Kurdish)&hl=en&sa=X&ei=DY5DU7jKJ4qc2QXYhYCACQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Kars%20(about%2020%20percent%20Kurdish)&f=false 167]}}</ref> and has a sizable Azerbaijani minority ([[K\u00fcres\u00fcnni]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kuresunniler.com/245/kuresunnilerin-turkiyede-yasadiklari-yerler/|title=K\u00fcres\u00fcnnilerin T\u00fcrkiye'de Ya\u015fad\u0131klar\u0131 Yerler - K\u00fcres\u00fcnniler Tarih ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Platformu|date=2014-04-12|work=K\u00fcres\u00fcnniler Tarih ve K\u00fclt\u00fcr Platformu|access-date=2018-04-08|language=tr-TR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kora-sonni|title=KORA-SONNI \u2013 Encyclopaedia Iranica|last=electricpulp.com|website=www.iranicaonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref> The current [[W\u0101li#Turkish term|Governor]] is Mehmet Emin Bilmez.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.van.gov.tr/|title=T.C. Van Valili\u011fi Resmi Web Sitesi|website=www.van.gov.tr|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThis area was the heartland of [[Armenians]], who lived in these areas from the time of Hayk in the 3rd millennium BCE right up to the late 19th century when the Ottoman Empire seized all the land from the natives.<ref>{{Cite book\n  | editor-last = Hofmann\n  | editor-first = Tessa \n  | title = Verfolgung, Vertreibung und Vernichtung der Christen im Osmanischen Reich 1912-1922 |trans-title=Persecution, Expulsion and Annihilation of the Christian Population in the Ottoman Empire 1912-1922\n  | publisher = M\u00fcnster: LIT\n  | year=2004\n  | isbn = 3-8258-7823-6}}</ref> In the 9th century BC the Van area was the center of the [[Urartu|Urartian kingdom]].<ref>European History in a World Perspective - p. 68 by Shepard Bancroft Clough</ref> The area was a major Armenian population center. The region came under the control of the [[Armenians|Armenian]] [[Orontid dynasty|Orontids]] in the 7th century BC and later [[Persian Empire|Persians]] in the mid-6th century BC. By the early 2nd century BC it was part of the [[Kingdom of Armenia (antiquity)|Kingdom of Armenia]]. It became an important center during the reign of the [[Armenia]]n king, [[Tigranes II of Armenia|Tigranes II]], who founded the city of [[Tigranocerta|Tigranakert]] in the 1st century BC.<ref>The Journal of Roman Studies \u2013 p. 124 by Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies</ref> With the Seljuq victory at the [[Battle of Malazgirt]] in 1071, just north of [[Lake Van]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historymedren.about.com/od/aentries/a/11_alparslan.htm|title=Alp Arslan: Article from the 1911 Encyclopedia|author= Melissa Snell|publisher=About Education}}</ref> it became a part of the [[Seljuq Empire]] and later the [[Ottoman Empire]] during their century long wars with their neighboring Iranian [[Safavid]] arch rivals, in which Selim I managed to conquer the area over the latter. The area continued to be contested and was passed on between the Ottoman Empire and the Safavids (and their subsequent successors, the [[Afsharids]] and [[Qajar dynasty|Qajars]]) for many centuries afterwards, all the way up to during the 19th century when it became the [[Van Vilayet]].\n\n=== In Turkey ===\nIn 1927 the office of the [[Inspector general|Inspector General]] was created, which governed with martial law.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=Jongerden|first=Joost|title=The Settlement Issue in Turkey and the Kurds: An Analysis of Spatical Policies, Modernity and War|date=2007-01-01|publisher=BRILL|year=2007|isbn=978-90-04-15557-2|location=|pages=53|language=en}}</ref> The province was included in the first [[Inspectorates-General (Turkey)|Inspectorate General]] (''Umumi M\u00fcfetti\u015flik,'' UM) over which the Inspector General ruled. The UM span over the provinces of [[Hakk\u00e2ri Province|Hakk\u00e2ri]], [[Siirt Province|Siirt]], Van, [[Mardin Province|Mardin]], [[Bitlis Province|Bitlis]], [[\u015eanl\u0131urfa Province|Sanl\u0131urfa]], [[Elaz\u0131\u011f Province|Elazi\u011f]] and [[Diyarbak\u0131r Province|Diyarbak\u0131r]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bayir|first=Derya|title=Minorities and Nationalism in Turkish Law|date=2016-04-22|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-09579-8|location=|pages=139|language=en}}</ref> The Inspectorate General were dissolved in 1952 during the Government of the [[Democrat Party (Turkey, 1946\u201361)|Democrat Party]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Fleet|first=Kate|title=The Cambridge History of Turkey|last2=Kunt|first2=I. Metin|last3=Kasaba|first3=Re\u015fat|last4=Faroqhi|first4=Suraiya|date=2008-04-17|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-521-62096-3|location=|pages=343|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBetween July 1987 and July 2000 Van Province was within the [[OHAL]] region, which was ruled by a Governor within a state of emergency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/pdfid/414d86ab4.pdf|title=Case of Dogan and others v. Turkey|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=21|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 November 2019}}</ref> \n\n==== Modern history ====\nAccording to the 2012 Metropolitan Municipalities Law (Law No. 6360), all Turkish provinces with a population more than 750 000, will have a [[Metropolitan municipalities in Turkey|metropolitan municipality]] and the [[List of districts of Turkey|districts]] within the metropolitan municipalities will be second level municipalities. The law also creates new districts within the provinces in addition to present districts.<ref>[http://www.resmigazete.gov.tr/eskiler/2012/12/20121206-1.htm Official gazette {{in lang|tr}}]</ref> These changes will be effective after the local elections in 2014.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nThus, in 2014, the city of [[Van, Turkey|Van]] became a Metropolitan Municipality.{{cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n== Earthquakes ==\nIn Van province occurred several earthquakes. In 1881 an earthquake occurred and caused the death of 95 people.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1941, Van suffered a destructive [[1941 Van\u2013Erci\u015f earthquake|5.9 M<sub>w</sub> earthquake]]. Two more [[2011 Van earthquakes|earthquakes occurred in 2011]] in which 644 people died and 2608 people were injured.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nat-hazards-earth-syst-sci.net/12/3337/2012/nhess-12-3337-2012.pdf|title=Van earthquakes (23 October 2011 and 9 November 2011) and performance of masonry and adobe structures|last=G\u00fcney|first=D.|date=|website=Natural Hazards and Earth System Sciences|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> In a [[2011 Van earthquake|7.2 M<sub>w</sub> earthquake]] on 23 October 2011, more than 500 people were killed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2011/11/09/world/turkey-earthquake/index.html|title=At least 5 dead in quake in eastern Turkey|last=Staff|first=By the CNN Wire|website=CNN|access-date=2020-03-01}}</ref> On 9 November 2011, a 5.6 M<sub>w</sub> magnitude earthquake killed also several people and caused buildings to collapse.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Districts ==\nVan Province is divided into 13 districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yenisafak.com/yerel-secim-2019/van-ili-secim-sonuclari|title=Van Se\u00e7im Sonu\u00e7lar\u0131 \u2013 31 Mart 2019 Van Yerel Se\u00e7im sonu\u00e7lar\u0131|last=\u015eafak|first=Yeni|date=2019-11-14|website=Yeni \u015eafak|language=tr-TR|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Bah\u00e7esaray (District), Van|Bah\u00e7esaray]]\n* [[Ba\u015fkale]]\n* [[\u00c7ald\u0131ran (District), Van|\u00c7ald\u0131ran]]\n* [[\u00c7atak (District), Van|\u00c7atak]]\n* [[Edremit (District), Van|Edremit]]\n* [[Erci\u015f]]\n* [[Geva\u015f]]\n* [[G\u00fcrp\u0131nar (District), Van|G\u00fcrp\u0131nar]]\n* [[\u0130pekyolu]]\n* [[Muradiye (District), Van|Muradiye]]\n* [[\u00d6zalp (District), Van|\u00d6zalp]]\n* [[Saray (District), Van|Saray]]\n* [[Tu\u015fpa]]\n}}\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Urartian fort in \u00c7avu\u015ftepe.jpg|[[Haykaberd]] or \u00c7avu\u015ftepe\nFile:Hosap-castle (17).jpg|[[Ho\u015fap Castle]]\nFile:Muradiye Falls 2.JPG|[[Muradiye Fall]]\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Medieval Armenian monasteries in the Van Province\">\nImage:Akdamar and mountain.jpg|The [[Armenian Cathedral of the Holy Cross]] (10th century) on [[Akdamar Island]]\nImage:Narekavank.jpg|The Armenian ''[[Narekavank|Monastery of Narek]]'' (10th century)\nImage:Varagavank.jpg|[[Varagavank]] Armenian monastery (11th century)\nImage:Saint Bartholomew Monastery.jpg|The Armenian '' [[Saint Bartholomew Monastery|Monastery of Saint Bartholomew]]'' (13th century)\n</gallery>\n<gallery caption=\"Islamic monuments in the Van Province\">\nFile:OTAltVanOsmanMoschee.jpg|Ruined Ottoman mosque in the old ruined part of Van city (16th century)\nFile:Geva\u015f T\u00fcrbe 01.JPG|Tomb of Halime Hatun in [[Geva\u015f]] (14th century)\nFile:OTAltVanOsmanMinarett.jpg|Ruined Ottoman minaret in the old part of Van city\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons category|Van Province}}\n* [[Ottoman Armenian Population]]\n* [[Defense of Van (1915)]]\n* [[2011 Van earthquake]]\n* [[Yazidis]]\n* [[2020 Van avalanches]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.pbase.com/dosseman/van Pictures of the capital of this province]\n\n{{coord|38|29|57|N|43|40|13|E|region:TR-65_type:adm1st|display=title}}\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Van}}\n{{Provinces of Turkey}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Van Province| ]]\n[[Category:Armenian Highlands]]\n[[Category:Turkish Kurdistan]]\n[[Category:Kurdish settlements]]\n", "name_user": "Biainili", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sorted by relevance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Van_Province"}
{"title_page": "THX 1138", "text_new": "{{about|the 1971 film|the high fidelity sound company|THX}}\n{{short description|1971 dystopian science fiction movie directed by George Lucas}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = THX 1138\n| image          = THX1138.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[George Lucas]]\n| producer       = Lawrence Sturhahn \n| screenplay     = {{Unbulleted list|George Lucas|[[Walter Murch]]}}\n| story          = George Lucas\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]''|George Lucas}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Duvall]]\n* [[Donald Pleasence]]\n* [[Don Pedro Colley]]\n* [[Maggie McOmie]]\n* [[Ian Wolfe]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Lalo Schifrin]]\n| cinematography = {{Unbulleted list|David Myers|Albert Kihn}}\n| editing        = George Lucas\n| studio         = [[American Zoetrope]]\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1971|03|11}}\n| runtime        = 86 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 85:25--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/thx-1138-1970-1 | title=''THX 1138'' (X) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=May 28, 1971 | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $777,777<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture>{{Cite AV media|date=2004|title=Artifact from the Future: The Making of THX 1138|medium=DVD bonus disk accompanying ''THX 1138: The George Lucas Director's Cut''|location=USA|publisher= Warner Bros.}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">Pollock 1983, p. 89.</ref>\n| gross          = $2.4 million\n}}\n'''''THX 1138''''' is a 1971 American [[social science fiction]] [[science fiction film|film]] directed by [[George Lucas]] in his [[feature film]] [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]]. It is set in a [[dystopia]]n future in which the populace is controlled through [[Android (robot)|android]] police and mandatory use of drugs that suppress emotions. Produced by [[Francis Ford Coppola]] and written by Lucas and [[Walter Murch]], it stars [[Robert Duvall]] and [[Donald Pleasence]].\n\n''THX 1138'' was developed from Lucas's student film ''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]'', which he made in 1967 while attending the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]]. The feature film was produced in a joint venture between [[Warner Bros.]] and [[American Zoetrope]]. A novelization by [[Ben Bova]] was published in 1971. The film received mixed reviews from critics and [[Box office bomb|failed to find box-office success]] on initial release; however, the film has subsequently received critical acclaim and gained a [[cult following]], particularly in the aftermath of Lucas' success with ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' in 1977.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please see WP:FILMPLOT for more information. The plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn the future, [[sexual intercourse]] and [[reproduction]] are prohibited, whereas use of [[Psychoactive drug|mind-altering drugs]] is mandatory to enforce compliance among the citizens and to ensure their ability to conduct dangerous and demanding tasks. Emotions and the concept of family are [[taboo]]. Everyone is clad in identical white uniforms and has shaven heads to emphasize uniformity, except the police [[android (robot)|android]]s (who wear black) and robed monks. Instead of names, people have designations with three arbitrary letters (referred to as the \"prefix\") and four digits, shown on an identity badge worn at all times.\n\nAt their jobs in central video <!-- CCTV --> control centers, SEN 5241 and LUH 3417 keep surveillance on the city. LUH has a male roommate, THX 1138, who works in a factory producing android police officers. At the beginning of the story, THX finishes his shift while the loudspeakers urge the workers to \"increase safety\"\u2014and congratulate them for only losing 195 workers in the last period\u2014to the competing factory's 242. On the way home, he stops at a confession booth in a row of many, and relates his concerns and mumbles prayers about \"party\" and \"masses\", under the [[Jesus Christ]]-esque portrait of \"OMM 0000\". A soothing voice greets THX, and OMM ends every [[Confession (religion)|confession]] with a parting salutation: \"You are a true believer, blessings of the State, blessings of the masses. Work hard, increase production, prevent accidents and be happy.\"\n\nAt home, THX takes his drugs and watches [[Holography|holobroadcasts]] while engaging with a masturbatory device. LUH secretly substitutes pills in her possession for THX's medications, causing him to develop nausea, anxiety, and sexual desires. LUH and THX become involved romantically and have sex. THX later is confronted by SEN, who arranges THX as his new roommate, but THX files a complaint against SEN for the illegal housing mate change. Without drugs in his system, THX falters during a critical and hazardous phase of his job, and a control center engages a \"mind lock\" on THX which raises the level of danger. After the release of the mind lock, THX makes the necessary correction to that work phase. THX and LUH are arrested and THX undergoes drug therapy. He enjoys a brief reunion with LUH, disrupted shortly after she reveals her pregnancy.\n\nAt THX's trial, THX is sentenced to prison, alongside SEN. Most of the prisoners seem uninterested in escape, but eventually THX and SEN find an exit, and they are later joined by [[Holography|hologram]] actor SRT 5752, who starred in the holobroadcasts. During the escape, THX and SRT are separated from SEN. Chased by the police robots, THX and SRT are trapped in a control center, from which THX learns that LUH has been \"consumed\", and her name has been reassigned to [[fetus]] 66691 in a growth chamber. SEN eventually escapes to an area reserved for the monks of OMM, where a lone monk notices that SEN has no identification badge. SEN attacks him and later wanders into a child-rearing area, strikes up a conversation with children and sits aimlessly until police androids apprehend him. THX and SRT steal two cars, but SRT crashes his into a concrete pillar.\n\nPursued by two police androids on motorcycles, THX flees to the limits of the city and escapes into a ventilation shaft. The police androids pursue him on motorcycles along the shaft to an escape ladder, but are ordered by Central Command to cease pursuit, on the grounds that the expense of his capture exceeds their allocated budget. The guards inform THX that the surface is uninhabitable but he is undeterred and continues up the ventilation shaft. The city is then revealed to be entirely underground, and THX has escaped onto the surface, where he then witnesses the sun setting. A bird can be seen flying in the distance, indicating that at least some life is still inhabiting the planet's surface.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Christ Giving His Blessing.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Hans Memling]]'s ''Christ Giving His Blessing'' (1478) is used as the visual representation of the [[State religion|state-sanctioned]] [[deity]] OMM 0000.<ref>Compare with [https://www.imdb.com/media/rm2820911104/tt0066434?ref_=ttmi_mi_all_sf_10 this image] from [[IMDb]].</ref>]]\n* [[Robert Duvall]] as THX 1138 \n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as SEN 5241\n* [[Maggie McOmie]] as LUH 3417\n* [[Don Pedro Colley]] as the hologram SRT\n* [[Ian Wolfe]] as the old prisoner PTO\n* [[Marshall Efron]] as prisoner TWA\n* [[Sid Haig]] as prisoner NCH\n* [[John Pearce (actor)|John Pearce]] as prisoner DWY\n* [[James Wheaton]] as the voice of OMM 0000\n* [[David Ogden Stiers]] (as David Ogden Steers) Narrator <ref>{{cite news |last1=Fox News |title=David Ogden Stiers, fussy 'M*A*S*H' doc and beloved clock from Disney's 'Beast,' dies at 75 |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/david-ogden-stiers-fussy-mash-doc-and-beloved-clock-from-disneys-beast-dies-at-75 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=Fox News |agency=Fox News Channel |publisher=Fox News}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''THX 1138'' was the first film made in a planned seven-picture slate commissioned by Warner Bros. from the 1969 incarnation of [[American Zoetrope]].<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 88.</ref><ref>Louise Sweeney, \"The Movie Business is alive and well and living in San Francisco\", ''Show'', April 1970.</ref> Lucas wrote the initial script draft based on his earlier short film but Coppola and Lucas agreed it was unsatisfactory. Murch assisted Lucas in writing an improved final draft.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"auto\" /> For some of SEN's dialogue in the film, the script included excerpts from speeches by [[Richard Nixon]].<ref name=\"Lucas 2004\">Lucas 2004.</ref>\n\nThe script required almost the entire cast to shave their heads, either completely bald or with a [[buzz cut]]. As a publicity stunt, several actors were filmed having their first haircuts/shaves at unusual venues, with the results used in a promotional featurette titled ''[[Bald: The Making of THX 1138]]''. Many of the shaven-headed extras seen in the film were recruited from the nearby addiction recovery program [[Synanon]].<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 92.</ref>\n\nFilming began on September 22, 1969.<ref>Lawrence Sturhahn, \"Genesis of THX-1138: Notes on a Production\", ''Kansas Quarterly'', Spring 1972.</ref> The schedule was between 35 and 40 days, completing in November 1969. Lucas filmed ''THX 1138'' in [[Techniscope]].<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref>Pollock 1983, pp. 90, 280.</ref>\n\nMost locations for filming were in the [[San Francisco]] area,<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 91\">Pollock 1983, p. 91.</ref> including the unfinished tunnels of the [[Bay Area Rapid Transit]] subway system,<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 91\" /><ref name=Chron>Katie Dowd, [https://www.sfgate.com/sfhistory/article/bart-transbay-tube-construction-photos-george-luca-13671480.php#photo-12468805 \"Before BART opened the Transbay Tube, they let George Lucas film a movie inside\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', March 10, 2019.</ref> the [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]],<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> the [[Marin County Civic Center]] in [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] designed by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]],<ref name=Chron/> the [[Lawrence Hall of Science]] in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]],<ref name=Chron/> the [[San Francisco International Airport]],<ref name=Chron/> and at a [[remote manipulator]] for a [[hot cell]]. Studio sequences were shot at stages in Los Angeles, including a white stage {{convert|100|by|150|ft}} for the \"white limbo\" sequences.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> Lucas used entirely natural light.<ref name=Chron/>\n\nThe chase scene featured two [[Lola T70]] Mk III race cars<ref>{{cite news |last=Breeze |first=Joe |date=5 January 2015 |title=The police drove Lola T70s in George Lucas's directorial debut |url=https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/cars/police-drove-lola-t70s-george-lucass-directorial-debut |newspaper=Classic Driver |access-date=5 December 2015}}</ref> being chased by [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]] TA125/250cc two-stroke, race-replica motorcycles through two [[San Francisco Bay Area]] automotive tunnels: the [[Caldecott Tunnel]] between [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and [[Orinda, California|Orinda]]; and the underwater [[Posey and Webster Street tubes|Posey Tube]] between Oakland and [[Alameda, California|Alameda]].<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> According to [[Caleb Deschanel]], cars drove at speeds of {{convert|140|mph}} while filming the chase.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> Other cars appearing in several scenes of the movie include the custom-built Ferrari Thomassima cars; one of them is on display in the [[Museo Casa Enzo Ferrari|Ferrari museum]] in [[Modena|Modena, Italy]].<ref name=\"Thomassima.com\">\"Thomassima III is on display in the new Ferrari Museum in Modena\".{{Cite web|url=http://thomassima.com/|title=Meade of Modena: An American Dreamer In the Land of Artful Science|access-date=1 January 2017|work=Thomassima.com}}</ref>\n\nThe chase featured a motorcycle stunt. Stuntman Ronald \"Duffy\" Hambleton (credited as Duffy Hamilton) rode his police motorcycle full speed into a fallen paint stand, with a ramp built to Hambleton's specification. He flew over the handlebars, was hit by the airborne motorcycle, landed in the street on his back, and slammed into the crashed car in which Duvall's character had escaped.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> According to Lucas, it turned out Hambleton was perfectly fine, apart from being angry with the people who had run into the shot to check on him. He was worried that they might have ruined the amazing stunt he had just performed by walking into frame.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nTHX's final climb out to the daylight was filmed (with the camera rotated 90\u00b0) in the incomplete (and decidedly horizontal) Bay Area Rapid Transit [[Transbay Tube]] before installation of the track supports, with the actors using exposed reinforcing bars on the floor of the tunnel as a \"ladder\".<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> The end scene, of THX standing before the sunset, was shot at [[Port Hueneme, California]], by a second unit of (additional uncredited photographer) Caleb Deschanel and [[Matthew Robbins (screenwriter)|Matthew Robbins]], who played THX in this long shot.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture />\n\nAfter completion of photography, Coppola scheduled a year for Lucas to complete postproduction.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 96\">Pollock 1983, p. 96.</ref> Lucas edited the film on a German-made K-E-M [[flatbed editor]] in his Mill Valley house by day, with Walter Murch editing sound at night; the two compared notes when they changed over.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 96\" /> Murch compiled and synchronized the sound montage, which includes all the \"overhead\" voices heard throughout the film, radio chatter, announcements, etc. The bulk of the editing was finished by mid-1970.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nOn completion of editing of the film, producer Coppola took it to Warner Bros., the financiers. Studio executives there disliked the film, and insisted that Coppola turn over the negative to an in-house Warner editor, who cut about 4 minutes of the film prior to release.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 97\">Pollock 1983, p. 97.</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = THX 1138\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     =\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1970}}\n| recorded   = October 15\u201316, 1970\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[The Burbank Studios]], [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], California, U.S.\n| genre      = [[Experimental music|Experimental]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=55|s=36}}\n| label      =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack to the THX 1138, conducted by Lalo Schifrin, was released in 1970. Recording took place on October 15 and 16, 1970, at [[The Burbank Studios]] in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], California, U.S.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/thx-1138-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000551994 AllMusic]</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n#Logo \u2013 00:08\n#Main Title / What's Wrong? \u2013 03:14\n#Room Tone / Primitive Dance \u2013 01:46\n#Be Happy / LUH / Society Montage \u2013 05:06\n#Be Happy Again (Jingle of the Future) \u2013 00:56\n#Source #1 \u2013 05:18\n#Loneliness Sequence \u2013 01:28\n#SEN / Monks / LUH Reprise \u2013 02:44\n#You Have Nowhere to Go \u2013 01:12\n#Torture Sequence / Prison Talk Sequence \u2013 03:42\n#Love Dream / The Awakening \u2013 01:47\n#First Escape \u2013 03:01\n#Source #3 \u2013 03:34\n#Second Escape \u2013 01:16\n#Source #4 / Third Escape / Morgue Sequence / The Temple / Disruption / LUH's Death \u2013 08:31\n#Source #2 \u2013 03:17\n#The Hologram \u2013 00:56\n#First Chase / Foot Chase / St. Matthew's Passion (Bach) (End Credits) \u2013 07:40\n\n==Reception==\n''THX 1138'' was released to theaters on March 11, 1971 and was a commercial flop, earning back $945,000 in rentals for Warner Bros. but still leaving the studio in the red.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 97\" /> A contemporary survey found seven favorable, three mixed, and five negative reviews.<ref>\"THX 1138\", ''FilmFacts'', Vol XIV, No.7, 1971.</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' rated the film three stars out of four and wrote, \"'THX 1138' suffers somewhat from its simple storyline, but as a work of visual imagination it's special, and as haunting as parts of '[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]],' '[[Silent Running]]' and '[[The Andromeda Strain (film)|The Andromeda Strain]].'\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/thx-1138-2004 |title=THX 1138 |last=Ebert |first=Roger |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 }}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' awarded two stars out four and stated, \"The principal problem with this film is that it lacks imagination, the essential component of a science fiction film. Some persons might claim that the world of 'THX 1138' is here right now. A more reasonable opinion would hold that we are facing the problems of that world right now. Time has passed the film by.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (May 18, 1971). \"THX 1138\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 4.</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"It is not, however, as either chase drama, or social drama, that 'THX 1138' is most interesting. Rather it's as a stunning montage of light, color and sound effects that create their own emotional impact ... Lucas's achievement in his first feature is all the more extraordinary when you realize that he is 25 years old, and that he shot most of the film in San Francisco, on a budget that probably would not cover the cost of half of one of the space ships in Stanley Kubrick's '2001.'\"<ref>Canby, Vincent (March 21, 1971). [https://www.nytimes.com/1971/03/21/archives/wandas-a-wow-sos-thx-wandas-a-wow-sos-thx.html \"Wanda's a Wow, So's THX\".] ''[[The New York Times]]''. Section 2, p. 11.</ref> Arthur D. Murphy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' observed, \"Likely not to be an artistic or commercial success in its own time, the American Zoetrope (Francis Ford Coppola group) production just might in time become a classic of stylistic, abstract cinema.\"<ref>Murphy, Arthur D. (March 17, 1971). \"Film Reviews: THX 1138\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 18.</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' praised the film as \"a stunning deployment of the aural and visual resources of the screen to suggest a fearful new world of tyranny by technology,\" adding that \"Lucas is obviously a master of cinematic effects with a special remarkable gift for discovering the look of the future in mundane places like parking structures and office corridors.\" Champlin stressed that the \"real excitement of 'THX 1138' is not really the message but the medium\u2014the use of film not to tell a story so much as to convey an experience, a credible impression of a fantastic and scary dictatorship of tomorrow.\"<ref>Champlin, Charles (March 11, 1971). \"New World of Tyranny in 'THX'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 1.</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] wrote in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', \"Fortunately, the film comes over not at all trite but rather as enormously affecting. Lucas obviously believed strongly in this futuristic vision, and the film draws its vitality and unity from his belief, and from the fact that it was not bottled up to meet arbitrary conditions but allowed the free rein necessary to reach completeness.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (April 17, 1971). \"THX 1138\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C6.</ref> Penelope Houston of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' commented, \"Details of the future society\u2014control panels, monitor screens, soothing TV commercial voices, unshakeably calm robot policemen, the human animal turned automaton in appearance and function, but breaking out into a doomed love affair\u2014are all tolerably persuasive, but in sum total rather a pile-up of predictability. On the Orwellian level of ideas, Lucas' passive new world is too indeterminate to carry enough conviction and, consequently, enough of a menacing charge.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Houston |first=Penelope |date=July 1971 |title=THX 1138 |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=38 |issue=450 |page=148 }}</ref>\n\nThe film has continued to earn critical acclaim and is currently rated \"fresh\" on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 63 reviews, with a score of 86% and an average rating of 6.85/10. The consensus reads: \"George Lucas' feature debut presents a spare, bleak, dystopian future, and features evocatively minimal set design and creepy sound effects.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thx_1138 |title=THX 1138 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=2013-04-08}}</ref> The film has a score of 75/100 at [[Metacritic]] indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THX 1138 Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/thx-1138|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nThe film received a nomination at the 1971 [[Cannes Film Festival]] from the [[International Federation of Film Critics]] in the [[Director's Fortnight]] section.\n\n==Versions==\n===1967 student film===\nThe first version was a student film for [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]] entitled ''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]''. The run time was 15 minutes. It was released as a bonus feature on the 2004 Directors' Cut.\n\n===1971 studio version===\nThe 1971 studio version, distributed to theaters, had five minutes taken out (apparently against Lucas' wishes) by Warner Bros. studios. This version (81 minutes long) has never been released on any home media format.\n\n===1977 restored version===\nIn 1977, after the success of ''Star Wars'', ''THX 1138'' was re-released with the footage that had been deleted by Warner Bros. edited back in, but it still did not gain popularity.<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 98.</ref> This version (86 minutes) was subsequently released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]].\n\n===2004 director's cut===\n[[File:THX 1138 DC.png|upright=1.6|thumbnail|right|''The George Lucas Director's Cut'' includes completely new footage, as seen in this shot of the factory where THX works.]]\nIn 2004, ''The George Lucas Director's Cut'' of the film was released. Under Lucas' supervision, the film underwent an extensive restoration and [[digital intermediate]] process by [[Lowry Digital]] and [[Industrial Light & Magic]] (ILM), where the film's [[negative (photography)|original negative]] was scanned, digital [[color correction]] was applied, and a brand new [[digital master]] was created.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lucasfilm.com/thx-1138|title=THX 1138 by Lucasfilm|work=lucasfilm.com|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> [[Computer-generated imagery]] and audio/video restoration techniques were applied to the film.<ref>{{cite interview |interviewer=Bill Desowitz |subject1=Paul Hill |subject2=Henry Preston |date=October 11, 2004 |url=http://www.awn.com/vfxworld/back-future-thx-1138 |title=Back to the Future with 'THX 1138' |work=AWN.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maverick-media.co.uk/movies/thx_1138_1971/changes_001.html |title=THX 1138 (1971)\u2014Changes |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502060328/http://www.maverick-media.co.uk/movies/thx_1138_1971/changes_001.html |archive-date=May 2, 2009 |publisher=Maverick Media |access-date=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\nAt Lucas' request, ILM and [[The Third Floor, Inc.|The Third Floor]] created new digital special effects and shot new footage, mostly to expand scenes by extending crowds, filling out settings, and adding detail to the backgrounds of many scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thethirdfloorinc.com/publish/features-f4d39/thx-1138-the-george-lucas-directors-cut-17966a.html|title=The Third Floor|work=thethirdfloorinc.com|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The shell dwellers, seen briefly in the beginning of the film (played by dwarves in monkey costumes), are augmented at the end of the film by several [[computer-generated imagery]] dog-people which look very different from the live actors in costume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/THX-1138-George-Lucas-Director-Cut-668.html|title=THX 1138: The George Lucas Director's Cut|date=May 27, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> These changes increased the run time of the film to 88 minutes. This [[director's cut]] was released to a limited number of digital-projection theaters on September 10, 2004, and then on [[DVD]] on September 14, 2004. The film was released on [[Blu-ray]] on September 7, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=4591|title=Warner Announces Sci-Fi Blu-ray Wave|last=Calonge|first=Juan|date=May 10, 2010|publisher=Blu-ray.com|access-date=2010-07-26}}</ref> At that time, the film received an \"R\" rating (for \"sexuality/nudity\") from the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], due to the changes to the ratings system since the original release (the original film was rated \"GP\", later changed to \"PG\"). It is the only film directed by Lucas to carry an \"R\" rating.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n===Novelization===\nA [[novelization]] based on the film was written by [[Ben Bova]] and published in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/THX-1138-Ben-Bova/dp/0446897116|title=THX 1138|first1=Ben|last1=Bova|first2=George|last2=Lucas|date=February 1, 1978|publisher=Warner Books|access-date=December 27, 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref> It follows the plot of the movie closely, with four notable additions:\n* An additional character, Control, is the accountant-like ultimate administrator of the city. Several passages depict the events from his point of view.\n* After having sex with LUH 3417, THX 1138 consults a psychologist and admits everything. This psychologist transfers the confession to Control, leading to the overriding mindlock and arrest in the factory.\n* LUH 3417's trial and death are depicted first-hand from her point of view, and from that of Control.\n* Instead of climbing outside to witness a sunset, THX 1138 climbs up and spends the night in the superstructure, and exits in the morning to find other humans living outside.\n\n==Origin of the name==\nThe significance of the name THX 1138 has been the subject of much speculation. In an interview for the DVD compilation ''Reel Talent'', which included Lucas's original ''4EB'' short, Lucas stated that he chose the letters and numbers for their aesthetic qualities, especially their symmetry.<ref>''Reel Talent: First Films by Legendary Directors'', DVD, 20th Century Fox, 2007</ref> According to the book ''Cinema by the Bay'', published by LucasBooks, Lucas named the film after his telephone number while in college: 849-1138\u2014the letters THX correspond to the numbers 8, 4, and 9 on the keypad.<ref name=ByTheBay>{{cite book|title=Cinema By The Bay|year=2006|publisher=George Lucas Books|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-932183-88-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/cinemabybay0000avni/page/36 36]|author=Sheerly Avni|edition=Hardcover|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/cinemabybay0000avni/page/36}}</ref> Walter Murch states in the DVD's audio commentary that he always believed Lucas intended THX to be \"sex\", LUH to be \"love\", and SEN to be \"sin\".<ref name=\"Lucas 2004\" /> John Lithgow, in \"The Film School Generation\" segment of the DVD series ''American Cinema'', described the title THX 1138 as \"reading like a license plate number.\"<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Lithgow, John (host)\n | year = 1995\n | title =American Cinema: The Film School Generation\n | medium =Television Production\n}}</ref>\n\nNumerous references to \"1138\" or \"THX 1138\" appear throughout the ''Star Wars'' films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/beyond-a-cell-block-references-to-thx-1138-in-star-wars|title=Beyond a Cell Block: References to THX 1138 in Star Wars |date=September 15, 2015|publisher=StarWars.com}}</ref> as well as other films by George Lucas. For example, THX 138 is the license plate number of John Milner's hot rod in ''[[American Graffiti]]''. Lucas also founded [[THX|THX Ltd.]], developer of the \"THX\" audio/visual reproduction standards.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* ''THX 1138'' has proven very popular as a source of audio samples in electronic music, almost as popular as ''[[Blade Runner]]''. Bands that have sampled ''THX 1138'' include [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[The Shamen]], [[Orbital (band)|Orbital]], [[Laibach]], [[Front 242]], [[Unkle]], [[DJ Shadow]], etc.<ref>{{cite web |title=THX 1138 (1971) |url=https://www.whosampled.com/movie/THX-1138/ |website=WhoSampled |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n* \"[[We Are 138]]\", a 1978 song by [[Misfits (band)|the Misfits]], is commonly said to have been inspired by ''THX 1138''.{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}} Misfits bassist [[Jerry Only]] and former Misfits guitarist [[Bobby Steele]] have reportedly supported this interpretation,{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/misfits-band-movies-inspiration-horror-halloween/|title=10 Movies That Inspired The Misfits|last=Downey|first=Ryan J.|date=October 29, 2018|website=[[MovieWeb]]|access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=misfitscentral>{{cite web|url=http://www.misfitscentral.com/misfits/songname.php|title=The Misfits Trivia|website=Misfits Central|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> though writer and vocalist [[Glenn Danzig]] has denied the claim, stating that his former bandmates \"didn't write it, and they don't know what the fuck it's about. It's about violence.\"{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}}<ref name=misfitscentral /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://diffuser.fm/things-you-didnt-know-about-the-misfits/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About the Misfits|last=Levith|first=Will|date=July 7, 2013|website=[[Diffuser.fm]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n* \"[[99 (song)|99]]\", a 1979 song by [[Toto (band)|Toto]], was written as a tribute to the film and the [[music video]] resembles a scene in it.<ref name=\"amg1\">{{cite web |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Jason |last=Elias |title=Song Review: 99\u2014Toto |url={{AllMusic|class=song|id=t3273785|pure_url=yes}} |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"foro\">{{cite news |work=[[Reforma]] |title=De 'Africa' al Foro |first=Edmundo Garc\u00eda |last=Salda\u00f1a |language=Spanish |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-4074835_ITM |date=October 19, 2001 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"hono\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Ryan |work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |title=TOTO flies high on tour |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2004/05/07/features/story4.html |date=May 7, 2004 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"t99\">{{cite web |publisher=The Official Toto Website |work=Toto Encyclopedia |title=99 |url=http://www.toto99.com/blog/ency.php?/archives/360-99.html |date=April 28, 2007 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref> In the music video, as in the film scene where the main character THX 1138 is imprisoned, the room is completely white and everyone wears a white jumpsuit.<ref name=\"t99\" /> ''Toto Legend'', the former official International Toto Fan Club newsletter, reviewed the video: <blockquote>'99' was predominantly a performance video, though the set design was rather conceptual. Following [[David Paich]]'s intention regarding the lyrics, about a sterile society in which names are forgotten and love forbidden, the set was sterile white, with various sized sculptured 99's hanging and standing about, and the band was clad in futuristic white jumpsuits. There were some notable shots in this one\u2014keyboard close-ups and an artistic view of [[Jeff Porcaro|Jeff]] through a transparent drum head, a technique that several popular videos have copied since.<ref name=\"t99\" /></blockquote>\n* In an episode of the American animated television series ''[[Futurama]]'', the characters visit a bar with the name \"TEX 1138's\".<ref>[https://theinfosphere.org/Tex_1138%27s Tex 1138's]</ref>\n* In 2015, [[Asian Dub Foundation]] toured with their live soundtrack to ''THX 1138''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Asian Dub Foundation\u2019s THX1138 |url=https://www.colstonhall.org/shows/asian-dub-foundations-thx1138/ |website=Colston Hall |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Asian Dub Foundation live score THX 1138 |url=https://brightondome.org/event/7662/asian_dub_foundation_live_score_thx_1138/ |website=Brighton Dome |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[Spotify]], by typing THX1138 in the search bar, all music sliders will turn into lightsabers.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1971]]\n* [[Utopian and dystopian fiction]]\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{cite book|last=Greene, Jr.|first=James|title=This Music Leaves Stains: The Complete Story of the Misfits|year=2013|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=978-1589798922|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pollock|first=Dale|authorlink=|others=|title=Skywalking: The Life and Films of George Lucas|year=1983|publisher=Elm Tree Books|location=London|isbn=0-241-11034-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media | people=Lucas, George (Director) |date=2004 | title=THX 1138 (The George Lucas Director's Cut Two-Disc Special Edition) | medium=DVD | location=USA | publisher= Warner Bros. |oclc=56520465 | isbn=0-7907-6526-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.lucasfilm.com/productions/thx-1138/}} at lucasfilm.com\n* {{Official website|https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/thx-1138/}} at warnerbros.com\n* {{IMDb title|66434}}\n* [http://www.lucasfan.com/thx1138/interv.html Interview with Don Pedro Colley about his experiences working on ''THX 1138''] at LucasFan.com\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2010/11/thx-1138_george.php White on White] [[Village Voice]] review April 8, 1971\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|thx_1138}}\n\n{{George Lucas}}\n{{Lucasfilm}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thx 1138}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1971 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American Zoetrope films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Cinema of the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Features based on short films]]\n[[Category:Films about rebellions]]\n[[Category:Films about security and surveillance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Lalo Schifrin]]\n[[Category:In-jokes]]\n[[Category:Fiction about mind control]]\n[[Category:Religion in science fiction]]\n[[Category:American robot films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Social science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1971 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1971 film|the high fidelity sound company|THX}}\n{{short description|1971 dystopian science fiction movie directed by George Lucas}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = THX 1138\n| image          = THX1138.jpg\n| image_size     = 250px\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[George Lucas]]\n| producer       = Lawrence Sturhahn \n| screenplay     = {{Unbulleted list|George Lucas|[[Walter Murch]]}}\n| story          = George Lucas\n| based_on       = {{based on|''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]''|George Lucas}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Duvall]]\n* [[Donald Pleasence]]\n* [[Don Pedro Colley]]\n* [[Maggie McOmie]]\n* [[Ian Wolfe]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Lalo Schifrin]]\n| cinematography = {{Unbulleted list|David Myers|Albert Kihn}}\n| editing        = George Lucas\n| studio         = [[American Zoetrope]]\n| distributor    = [[Warner Bros.]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1971|03|11}}\n| runtime        = 86 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 85:25--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/thx-1138-1970-1 | title=''THX 1138'' (X) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=May 28, 1971 | accessdate=November 19, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $777,777<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture>{{Cite AV media|date=2004|title=Artifact from the Future: The Making of THX 1138|medium=DVD bonus disk accompanying ''THX 1138: The George Lucas Director's Cut''|location=USA|publisher= Warner Bros.}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">Pollock 1983, p. 89.</ref>\n| gross          = $2.4 million\n}}\n'''''THX 1138''''' is a 1971 American [[social science fiction]] [[science fiction film|film]] directed by [[George Lucas]] in his [[feature film]] [[List of directorial debuts|directorial debut]]. It is set in a [[dystopia]]n future in which the populace is controlled through [[Android (robot)|android]] police and mandatory use of drugs that suppress emotions. Produced by [[Francis Ford Coppola]] and written by Lucas and [[Walter Murch]], it stars [[Robert Duvall]] and [[Donald Pleasence]].\n\n''THX 1138'' was developed from Lucas's student film ''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]'', which he made in 1967 while attending the [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]]. The feature film was produced in a joint venture between [[Warner Bros.]] and [[American Zoetrope]]. A novelization by [[Ben Bova]] was published in 1971. The film received mixed reviews from critics and [[Box office bomb|failed to find box-office success]] on initial release; however, the film has subsequently received critical acclaim and gained a [[cult following]], particularly in the aftermath of Lucas' success with ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' in 1977.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Please see WP:FILMPLOT for more information. The plot summary should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn the future, [[sexual intercourse]] and [[reproduction]] are prohibited, whereas use of [[Psychoactive drug|mind-altering drugs]] is mandatory to enforce compliance among the citizens and to ensure their ability to conduct dangerous and demanding tasks. Emotions and the concept of family are [[taboo]]. Everyone is clad in identical white uniforms and has shaven heads to emphasize uniformity, except the police [[android (robot)|android]]s (who wear black) and robed monks. Instead of names, people have designations with three arbitrary letters (referred to as the \"prefix\") and four digits, shown on an identity badge worn at all times.\n\nAt their jobs in central video <!-- CCTV --> control centers, SEN 5241 and LUH 3417 keep surveillance on the city. LUH has a male roommate, THX 1138, who works in a factory producing android police officers. At the beginning of the story, THX finishes his shift while the loudspeakers urge the workers to \"increase safety\"\u2014and congratulate them for only losing 195 workers in the last period\u2014to the competing factory's 242. On the way home, he stops at a confession booth in a row of many, and relates his concerns and mumbles prayers about \"party\" and \"masses\", under the [[Jesus Christ]]-esque portrait of \"OMM 0000\". A soothing voice greets THX, and OMM ends every [[Confession (religion)|confession]] with a parting salutation: \"You are a true believer, blessings of the State, blessings of the masses. Work hard, increase production, prevent accidents and be happy.\"\n\nAt home, THX takes his drugs and watches [[Holography|holobroadcasts]] while engaging with a masturbatory device. LUH secretly substitutes pills in her possession for THX's medications, causing him to develop nausea, anxiety, and sexual desires. LUH and THX become involved romantically and have sex. THX later is confronted by SEN, who arranges THX as his new roommate, but THX files a complaint against SEN for the illegal housing mate change. Without drugs in his system, THX falters during a critical and hazardous phase of his job, and a control center engages a \"mind lock\" on THX which raises the level of danger. After the release of the mind lock, THX makes the necessary correction to that work phase. THX and LUH are arrested and THX undergoes drug therapy. He enjoys a brief reunion with LUH, disrupted shortly after she reveals her pregnancy.\n\nAt THX's trial, THX is sentenced to prison, alongside SEN. Most of the prisoners seem uninterested in escape, but eventually THX and SEN find an exit, and they are later joined by [[Holography|hologram]] actor SRT 5752, who starred in the holobroadcasts. During the escape, THX and SRT are separated from SEN. Chased by the police robots, THX and SRT are trapped in a control center, from which THX learns that LUH has been \"consumed\", and her name has been reassigned to [[fetus]] 66691 in a growth chamber. SEN eventually escapes to an area reserved for the monks of OMM, where a lone monk notices that SEN has no identification badge. SEN attacks him and later wanders into a child-rearing area, strikes up a conversation with children and sits aimlessly until police androids apprehend him. THX and SRT steal two cars, but SRT crashes his into a concrete pillar.\n\nPursued by two police androids on motorcycles, THX flees to the limits of the city and escapes into a ventilation shaft. The police androids pursue him on motorcycles along the shaft to an escape ladder, but are ordered by Central Command to cease pursuit, on the grounds that the expense of his capture exceeds their allocated budget. The guards inform THX that the surface is uninhabitable but he is undeterred and continues up the ventilation shaft. The city is then revealed to be entirely underground, and THX has escaped onto the surface, where he then witnesses the sun setting. A bird can be seen flying in the distance, indicating that at least some life is still inhabiting the planet's surface.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Christ Giving His Blessing.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Hans Memling]]'s ''Christ Giving His Blessing'' (1478) is used as the visual representation of the [[State religion|state-sanctioned]] [[deity]] OMM 0000.<ref>Compare with [https://www.imdb.com/media/rm2820911104/tt0066434?ref_=ttmi_mi_all_sf_10 this image] from [[IMDb]].</ref>]]\n* [[Robert Duvall]] as THX 1138 \n* [[Donald Pleasence]] as SEN 5241\n* [[Maggie McOmie]] as LUH 3417\n* [[Don Pedro Colley]] as the hologram SRT\n* [[Ian Wolfe]] as the old prisoner PTO\n* [[Marshall Efron]] as prisoner TWA\n* [[Sid Haig]] as prisoner NCH\n* [[John Pearce (actor)|John Pearce]] as prisoner DWY\n* [[James Wheaton]] as the voice of OMM 0000\n\n==Production==\n''THX 1138'' was the first film made in a planned seven-picture slate commissioned by Warner Bros. from the 1969 incarnation of [[American Zoetrope]].<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 88.</ref><ref>Louise Sweeney, \"The Movie Business is alive and well and living in San Francisco\", ''Show'', April 1970.</ref> Lucas wrote the initial script draft based on his earlier short film but Coppola and Lucas agreed it was unsatisfactory. Murch assisted Lucas in writing an improved final draft.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"auto\" /> For some of SEN's dialogue in the film, the script included excerpts from speeches by [[Richard Nixon]].<ref name=\"Lucas 2004\">Lucas 2004.</ref>\n\nThe script required almost the entire cast to shave their heads, either completely bald or with a [[buzz cut]]. As a publicity stunt, several actors were filmed having their first haircuts/shaves at unusual venues, with the results used in a promotional featurette titled ''[[Bald: The Making of THX 1138]]''. Many of the shaven-headed extras seen in the film were recruited from the nearby addiction recovery program [[Synanon]].<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 92.</ref>\n\nFilming began on September 22, 1969.<ref>Lawrence Sturhahn, \"Genesis of THX-1138: Notes on a Production\", ''Kansas Quarterly'', Spring 1972.</ref> The schedule was between 35 and 40 days, completing in November 1969. Lucas filmed ''THX 1138'' in [[Techniscope]].<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref>Pollock 1983, pp. 90, 280.</ref>\n\nMost locations for filming were in the [[San Francisco]] area,<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 91\">Pollock 1983, p. 91.</ref> including the unfinished tunnels of the [[Bay Area Rapid Transit]] subway system,<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 91\" /><ref name=Chron>Katie Dowd, [https://www.sfgate.com/sfhistory/article/bart-transbay-tube-construction-photos-george-luca-13671480.php#photo-12468805 \"Before BART opened the Transbay Tube, they let George Lucas film a movie inside\"], ''San Francisco Chronicle'', March 10, 2019.</ref> the [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]],<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> the [[Marin County Civic Center]] in [[San Rafael, California|San Rafael]] designed by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]],<ref name=Chron/> the [[Lawrence Hall of Science]] in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]],<ref name=Chron/> the [[San Francisco International Airport]],<ref name=Chron/> and at a [[remote manipulator]] for a [[hot cell]]. Studio sequences were shot at stages in Los Angeles, including a white stage {{convert|100|by|150|ft}} for the \"white limbo\" sequences.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> Lucas used entirely natural light.<ref name=Chron/>\n\nThe chase scene featured two [[Lola T70]] Mk III race cars<ref>{{cite news |last=Breeze |first=Joe |date=5 January 2015 |title=The police drove Lola T70s in George Lucas's directorial debut |url=https://www.classicdriver.com/en/article/cars/police-drove-lola-t70s-george-lucass-directorial-debut |newspaper=Classic Driver |access-date=5 December 2015}}</ref> being chased by [[Yamaha Motor Company|Yamaha]] TA125/250cc two-stroke, race-replica motorcycles through two [[San Francisco Bay Area]] automotive tunnels: the [[Caldecott Tunnel]] between [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] and [[Orinda, California|Orinda]]; and the underwater [[Posey and Webster Street tubes|Posey Tube]] between Oakland and [[Alameda, California|Alameda]].<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> According to [[Caleb Deschanel]], cars drove at speeds of {{convert|140|mph}} while filming the chase.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> Other cars appearing in several scenes of the movie include the custom-built Ferrari Thomassima cars; one of them is on display in the [[Museo Casa Enzo Ferrari|Ferrari museum]] in [[Modena|Modena, Italy]].<ref name=\"Thomassima.com\">\"Thomassima III is on display in the new Ferrari Museum in Modena\".{{Cite web|url=http://thomassima.com/|title=Meade of Modena: An American Dreamer In the Land of Artful Science|access-date=1 January 2017|work=Thomassima.com}}</ref>\n\nThe chase featured a motorcycle stunt. Stuntman Ronald \"Duffy\" Hambleton (credited as Duffy Hamilton) rode his police motorcycle full speed into a fallen paint stand, with a ramp built to Hambleton's specification. He flew over the handlebars, was hit by the airborne motorcycle, landed in the street on his back, and slammed into the crashed car in which Duvall's character had escaped.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> According to Lucas, it turned out Hambleton was perfectly fine, apart from being angry with the people who had run into the shot to check on him. He was worried that they might have ruined the amazing stunt he had just performed by walking into frame.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nTHX's final climb out to the daylight was filmed (with the camera rotated 90\u00b0) in the incomplete (and decidedly horizontal) Bay Area Rapid Transit [[Transbay Tube]] before installation of the track supports, with the actors using exposed reinforcing bars on the floor of the tunnel as a \"ladder\".<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /> The end scene, of THX standing before the sunset, was shot at [[Port Hueneme, California]], by a second unit of (additional uncredited photographer) Caleb Deschanel and [[Matthew Robbins (screenwriter)|Matthew Robbins]], who played THX in this long shot.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture />\n\nAfter completion of photography, Coppola scheduled a year for Lucas to complete postproduction.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 96\">Pollock 1983, p. 96.</ref> Lucas edited the film on a German-made K-E-M [[flatbed editor]] in his Mill Valley house by day, with Walter Murch editing sound at night; the two compared notes when they changed over.<ref name=ArtifactFromTheFuture /><ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 96\" /> Murch compiled and synchronized the sound montage, which includes all the \"overhead\" voices heard throughout the film, radio chatter, announcements, etc. The bulk of the editing was finished by mid-1970.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nOn completion of editing of the film, producer Coppola took it to Warner Bros., the financiers. Studio executives there disliked the film, and insisted that Coppola turn over the negative to an in-house Warner editor, who cut about 4 minutes of the film prior to release.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 97\">Pollock 1983, p. 97.</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = THX 1138\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     =\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1970}}\n| recorded   = October 15\u201316, 1970\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[The Burbank Studios]], [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], California, U.S.\n| genre      = [[Experimental music|Experimental]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=55|s=36}}\n| label      =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\n\nThe soundtrack to the THX 1138, conducted by Lalo Schifrin, was released in 1970. Recording took place on October 15 and 16, 1970, at [[The Burbank Studios]] in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], California, U.S.<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/thx-1138-original-motion-picture-soundtrack-mw0000551994 AllMusic]</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n#Logo \u2013 00:08\n#Main Title / What's Wrong? \u2013 03:14\n#Room Tone / Primitive Dance \u2013 01:46\n#Be Happy / LUH / Society Montage \u2013 05:06\n#Be Happy Again (Jingle of the Future) \u2013 00:56\n#Source #1 \u2013 05:18\n#Loneliness Sequence \u2013 01:28\n#SEN / Monks / LUH Reprise \u2013 02:44\n#You Have Nowhere to Go \u2013 01:12\n#Torture Sequence / Prison Talk Sequence \u2013 03:42\n#Love Dream / The Awakening \u2013 01:47\n#First Escape \u2013 03:01\n#Source #3 \u2013 03:34\n#Second Escape \u2013 01:16\n#Source #4 / Third Escape / Morgue Sequence / The Temple / Disruption / LUH's Death \u2013 08:31\n#Source #2 \u2013 03:17\n#The Hologram \u2013 00:56\n#First Chase / Foot Chase / St. Matthew's Passion (Bach) (End Credits) \u2013 07:40\n\n==Reception==\n''THX 1138'' was released to theaters on March 11, 1971 and was a commercial flop, earning back $945,000 in rentals for Warner Bros. but still leaving the studio in the red.<ref name=\"Pollock 1983, p. 97\" /> A contemporary survey found seven favorable, three mixed, and five negative reviews.<ref>\"THX 1138\", ''FilmFacts'', Vol XIV, No.7, 1971.</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' rated the film three stars out of four and wrote, \"'THX 1138' suffers somewhat from its simple storyline, but as a work of visual imagination it's special, and as haunting as parts of '[[2001: A Space Odyssey (film)|2001: A Space Odyssey]],' '[[Silent Running]]' and '[[The Andromeda Strain (film)|The Andromeda Strain]].'\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/thx-1138-2004 |title=THX 1138 |last=Ebert |first=Roger |website=[[RogerEbert.com]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019 }}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' awarded two stars out four and stated, \"The principal problem with this film is that it lacks imagination, the essential component of a science fiction film. Some persons might claim that the world of 'THX 1138' is here right now. A more reasonable opinion would hold that we are facing the problems of that world right now. Time has passed the film by.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (May 18, 1971). \"THX 1138\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 4.</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote, \"It is not, however, as either chase drama, or social drama, that 'THX 1138' is most interesting. Rather it's as a stunning montage of light, color and sound effects that create their own emotional impact ... Lucas's achievement in his first feature is all the more extraordinary when you realize that he is 25 years old, and that he shot most of the film in San Francisco, on a budget that probably would not cover the cost of half of one of the space ships in Stanley Kubrick's '2001.'\"<ref>Canby, Vincent (March 21, 1971). [https://www.nytimes.com/1971/03/21/archives/wandas-a-wow-sos-thx-wandas-a-wow-sos-thx.html \"Wanda's a Wow, So's THX\".] ''[[The New York Times]]''. Section 2, p. 11.</ref> Arthur D. Murphy of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' observed, \"Likely not to be an artistic or commercial success in its own time, the American Zoetrope (Francis Ford Coppola group) production just might in time become a classic of stylistic, abstract cinema.\"<ref>Murphy, Arthur D. (March 17, 1971). \"Film Reviews: THX 1138\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 18.</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' praised the film as \"a stunning deployment of the aural and visual resources of the screen to suggest a fearful new world of tyranny by technology,\" adding that \"Lucas is obviously a master of cinematic effects with a special remarkable gift for discovering the look of the future in mundane places like parking structures and office corridors.\" Champlin stressed that the \"real excitement of 'THX 1138' is not really the message but the medium\u2014the use of film not to tell a story so much as to convey an experience, a credible impression of a fantastic and scary dictatorship of tomorrow.\"<ref>Champlin, Charles (March 11, 1971). \"New World of Tyranny in 'THX'\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part IV, p. 1.</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]] wrote in ''[[The Washington Post]]'', \"Fortunately, the film comes over not at all trite but rather as enormously affecting. Lucas obviously believed strongly in this futuristic vision, and the film draws its vitality and unity from his belief, and from the fact that it was not bottled up to meet arbitrary conditions but allowed the free rein necessary to reach completeness.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (April 17, 1971). \"THX 1138\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C6.</ref> Penelope Houston of ''[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' commented, \"Details of the future society\u2014control panels, monitor screens, soothing TV commercial voices, unshakeably calm robot policemen, the human animal turned automaton in appearance and function, but breaking out into a doomed love affair\u2014are all tolerably persuasive, but in sum total rather a pile-up of predictability. On the Orwellian level of ideas, Lucas' passive new world is too indeterminate to carry enough conviction and, consequently, enough of a menacing charge.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Houston |first=Penelope |date=July 1971 |title=THX 1138 |journal=[[The Monthly Film Bulletin]] |volume=38 |issue=450 |page=148 }}</ref>\n\nThe film has continued to earn critical acclaim and is currently rated \"fresh\" on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 63 reviews, with a score of 86% and an average rating of 6.85/10. The consensus reads: \"George Lucas' feature debut presents a spare, bleak, dystopian future, and features evocatively minimal set design and creepy sound effects.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/thx_1138 |title=THX 1138 |website=Rotten Tomatoes |access-date=2013-04-08}}</ref> The film has a score of 75/100 at [[Metacritic]] indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=THX 1138 Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/thx-1138|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\nThe film received a nomination at the 1971 [[Cannes Film Festival]] from the [[International Federation of Film Critics]] in the [[Director's Fortnight]] section.\n\n==Versions==\n===1967 student film===\nThe first version was a student film for [[USC School of Cinematic Arts]] entitled ''[[Electronic Labyrinth: THX 1138 4EB]]''. The run time was 15 minutes. It was released as a bonus feature on the 2004 Directors' Cut.\n\n===1971 studio version===\nThe 1971 studio version, distributed to theaters, had five minutes taken out (apparently against Lucas' wishes) by Warner Bros. studios. This version (81 minutes long) has never been released on any home media format.\n\n===1977 restored version===\nIn 1977, after the success of ''Star Wars'', ''THX 1138'' was re-released with the footage that had been deleted by Warner Bros. edited back in, but it still did not gain popularity.<ref>Pollock 1983, p. 98.</ref> This version (86 minutes) was subsequently released on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]].\n\n===2004 director's cut===\n[[File:THX 1138 DC.png|upright=1.6|thumbnail|right|''The George Lucas Director's Cut'' includes completely new footage, as seen in this shot of the factory where THX works.]]\nIn 2004, ''The George Lucas Director's Cut'' of the film was released. Under Lucas' supervision, the film underwent an extensive restoration and [[digital intermediate]] process by [[Lowry Digital]] and [[Industrial Light & Magic]] (ILM), where the film's [[negative (photography)|original negative]] was scanned, digital [[color correction]] was applied, and a brand new [[digital master]] was created.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lucasfilm.com/thx-1138|title=THX 1138 by Lucasfilm|work=lucasfilm.com|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> [[Computer-generated imagery]] and audio/video restoration techniques were applied to the film.<ref>{{cite interview |interviewer=Bill Desowitz |subject1=Paul Hill |subject2=Henry Preston |date=October 11, 2004 |url=http://www.awn.com/vfxworld/back-future-thx-1138 |title=Back to the Future with 'THX 1138' |work=AWN.com |access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maverick-media.co.uk/movies/thx_1138_1971/changes_001.html |title=THX 1138 (1971)\u2014Changes |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502060328/http://www.maverick-media.co.uk/movies/thx_1138_1971/changes_001.html |archive-date=May 2, 2009 |publisher=Maverick Media |access-date=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\nAt Lucas' request, ILM and [[The Third Floor, Inc.|The Third Floor]] created new digital special effects and shot new footage, mostly to expand scenes by extending crowds, filling out settings, and adding detail to the backgrounds of many scenes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thethirdfloorinc.com/publish/features-f4d39/thx-1138-the-george-lucas-directors-cut-17966a.html|title=The Third Floor|work=thethirdfloorinc.com|access-date=December 27, 2016}}</ref> The shell dwellers, seen briefly in the beginning of the film (played by dwarves in monkey costumes), are augmented at the end of the film by several [[computer-generated imagery]] dog-people which look very different from the live actors in costume.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/THX-1138-George-Lucas-Director-Cut-668.html|title=THX 1138: The George Lucas Director's Cut|date=May 27, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> These changes increased the run time of the film to 88 minutes. This [[director's cut]] was released to a limited number of digital-projection theaters on September 10, 2004, and then on [[DVD]] on September 14, 2004. The film was released on [[Blu-ray]] on September 7, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=4591|title=Warner Announces Sci-Fi Blu-ray Wave|last=Calonge|first=Juan|date=May 10, 2010|publisher=Blu-ray.com|access-date=2010-07-26}}</ref> At that time, the film received an \"R\" rating (for \"sexuality/nudity\") from the [[Motion Picture Association of America|MPAA]], due to the changes to the ratings system since the original release (the original film was rated \"GP\", later changed to \"PG\"). It is the only film directed by Lucas to carry an \"R\" rating.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n===Novelization===\nA [[novelization]] based on the film was written by [[Ben Bova]] and published in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/THX-1138-Ben-Bova/dp/0446897116|title=THX 1138|first1=Ben|last1=Bova|first2=George|last2=Lucas|date=February 1, 1978|publisher=Warner Books|access-date=December 27, 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref> It follows the plot of the movie closely, with four notable additions:\n* An additional character, Control, is the accountant-like ultimate administrator of the city. Several passages depict the events from his point of view.\n* After having sex with LUH 3417, THX 1138 consults a psychologist and admits everything. This psychologist transfers the confession to Control, leading to the overriding mindlock and arrest in the factory.\n* LUH 3417's trial and death are depicted first-hand from her point of view, and from that of Control.\n* Instead of climbing outside to witness a sunset, THX 1138 climbs up and spends the night in the superstructure, and exits in the morning to find other humans living outside.\n\n==Origin of the name==\nThe significance of the name THX 1138 has been the subject of much speculation. In an interview for the DVD compilation ''Reel Talent'', which included Lucas's original ''4EB'' short, Lucas stated that he chose the letters and numbers for their aesthetic qualities, especially their symmetry.<ref>''Reel Talent: First Films by Legendary Directors'', DVD, 20th Century Fox, 2007</ref> According to the book ''Cinema by the Bay'', published by LucasBooks, Lucas named the film after his telephone number while in college: 849-1138\u2014the letters THX correspond to the numbers 8, 4, and 9 on the keypad.<ref name=ByTheBay>{{cite book|title=Cinema By The Bay|year=2006|publisher=George Lucas Books|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-1-932183-88-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/cinemabybay0000avni/page/36 36]|author=Sheerly Avni|edition=Hardcover|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/cinemabybay0000avni/page/36}}</ref> Walter Murch states in the DVD's audio commentary that he always believed Lucas intended THX to be \"sex\", LUH to be \"love\", and SEN to be \"sin\".<ref name=\"Lucas 2004\" /> John Lithgow, in \"The Film School Generation\" segment of the DVD series ''American Cinema'', described the title THX 1138 as \"reading like a license plate number.\"<ref>{{cite AV media\n | people =Lithgow, John (host)\n | year = 1995\n | title =American Cinema: The Film School Generation\n | medium =Television Production\n}}</ref>\n\nNumerous references to \"1138\" or \"THX 1138\" appear throughout the ''Star Wars'' films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/beyond-a-cell-block-references-to-thx-1138-in-star-wars|title=Beyond a Cell Block: References to THX 1138 in Star Wars |date=September 15, 2015|publisher=StarWars.com}}</ref> as well as other films by George Lucas. For example, THX 138 is the license plate number of John Milner's hot rod in ''[[American Graffiti]]''. Lucas also founded [[THX|THX Ltd.]], developer of the \"THX\" audio/visual reproduction standards.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* ''THX 1138'' has proven very popular as a source of audio samples in electronic music, almost as popular as ''[[Blade Runner]]''. Bands that have sampled ''THX 1138'' include [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[The Shamen]], [[Orbital (band)|Orbital]], [[Laibach]], [[Front 242]], [[Unkle]], [[DJ Shadow]], etc.<ref>{{cite web |title=THX 1138 (1971) |url=https://www.whosampled.com/movie/THX-1138/ |website=WhoSampled |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n* \"[[We Are 138]]\", a 1978 song by [[Misfits (band)|the Misfits]], is commonly said to have been inspired by ''THX 1138''.{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}} Misfits bassist [[Jerry Only]] and former Misfits guitarist [[Bobby Steele]] have reportedly supported this interpretation,{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/misfits-band-movies-inspiration-horror-halloween/|title=10 Movies That Inspired The Misfits|last=Downey|first=Ryan J.|date=October 29, 2018|website=[[MovieWeb]]|access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref><ref name=misfitscentral>{{cite web|url=http://www.misfitscentral.com/misfits/songname.php|title=The Misfits Trivia|website=Misfits Central|access-date=September 4, 2019}}</ref> though writer and vocalist [[Glenn Danzig]] has denied the claim, stating that his former bandmates \"didn't write it, and they don't know what the fuck it's about. It's about violence.\"{{sfn|Greene, Jr.|2013|p=22}}<ref name=misfitscentral /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://diffuser.fm/things-you-didnt-know-about-the-misfits/|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About the Misfits|last=Levith|first=Will|date=July 7, 2013|website=[[Diffuser.fm]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|access-date=September 5, 2019}}</ref>\n* \"[[99 (song)|99]]\", a 1979 song by [[Toto (band)|Toto]], was written as a tribute to the film and the [[music video]] resembles a scene in it.<ref name=\"amg1\">{{cite web |website=[[AllMusic]] |first=Jason |last=Elias |title=Song Review: 99\u2014Toto |url={{AllMusic|class=song|id=t3273785|pure_url=yes}} |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"foro\">{{cite news |work=[[Reforma]] |title=De 'Africa' al Foro |first=Edmundo Garc\u00eda |last=Salda\u00f1a |language=Spanish |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-4074835_ITM |date=October 19, 2001 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"hono\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Ryan |work=[[Honolulu Star-Bulletin]] |title=TOTO flies high on tour |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2004/05/07/features/story4.html |date=May 7, 2004 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"t99\">{{cite web |publisher=The Official Toto Website |work=Toto Encyclopedia |title=99 |url=http://www.toto99.com/blog/ency.php?/archives/360-99.html |date=April 28, 2007 |access-date=March 12, 2010}}</ref> In the music video, as in the film scene where the main character THX 1138 is imprisoned, the room is completely white and everyone wears a white jumpsuit.<ref name=\"t99\" /> ''Toto Legend'', the former official International Toto Fan Club newsletter, reviewed the video: <blockquote>'99' was predominantly a performance video, though the set design was rather conceptual. Following [[David Paich]]'s intention regarding the lyrics, about a sterile society in which names are forgotten and love forbidden, the set was sterile white, with various sized sculptured 99's hanging and standing about, and the band was clad in futuristic white jumpsuits. There were some notable shots in this one\u2014keyboard close-ups and an artistic view of [[Jeff Porcaro|Jeff]] through a transparent drum head, a technique that several popular videos have copied since.<ref name=\"t99\" /></blockquote>\n* In an episode of the American animated television series ''[[Futurama]]'', the characters visit a bar with the name \"TEX 1138's\".<ref>[https://theinfosphere.org/Tex_1138%27s Tex 1138's]</ref>\n* In 2015, [[Asian Dub Foundation]] toured with their live soundtrack to ''THX 1138''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Asian Dub Foundation\u2019s THX1138 |url=https://www.colstonhall.org/shows/asian-dub-foundations-thx1138/ |website=Colston Hall |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Asian Dub Foundation live score THX 1138 |url=https://brightondome.org/event/7662/asian_dub_foundation_live_score_thx_1138/ |website=Brighton Dome |accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n* In [[Spotify]], by typing THX1138 in the search bar, all music sliders will turn into lightsabers.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1971]]\n* [[Utopian and dystopian fiction]]\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{cite book|last=Greene, Jr.|first=James|title=This Music Leaves Stains: The Complete Story of the Misfits|year=2013|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=978-1589798922|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Pollock|first=Dale|authorlink=|others=|title=Skywalking: The Life and Films of George Lucas|year=1983|publisher=Elm Tree Books|location=London|isbn=0-241-11034-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite AV media | people=Lucas, George (Director) |date=2004 | title=THX 1138 (The George Lucas Director's Cut Two-Disc Special Edition) | medium=DVD | location=USA | publisher= Warner Bros. |oclc=56520465 | isbn=0-7907-6526-8}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.lucasfilm.com/productions/thx-1138/}} at lucasfilm.com\n* {{Official website|https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/thx-1138/}} at warnerbros.com\n* {{IMDb title|66434}}\n* [http://www.lucasfan.com/thx1138/interv.html Interview with Don Pedro Colley about his experiences working on ''THX 1138''] at LucasFan.com\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2010/11/thx-1138_george.php White on White] [[Village Voice]] review April 8, 1971\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|thx_1138}}\n\n{{George Lucas}}\n{{Lucasfilm}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thx 1138}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1971 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction action films]]\n[[Category:American Zoetrope films]]\n[[Category:Android (robot) films]]\n[[Category:Cinema of the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Dystopian films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Features based on short films]]\n[[Category:Films about rebellions]]\n[[Category:Films about security and surveillance]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Lalo Schifrin]]\n[[Category:In-jokes]]\n[[Category:Fiction about mind control]]\n[[Category:Religion in science fiction]]\n[[Category:American robot films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Social science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1971 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Banjohunter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:Added David Ogden Stiers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/THX_1138"}
